'''John David Morris'''<ref>{{Cite book | last1 =British Library | first1 = | title = The British Library general catalogue of printed books 1976 to 1982. | date = 1983 | publisher = K. G. Saur | location = London &#59; | isbn = 3-598-30500-1 | pages =192 }}</ref> (born 1946) is an [[United States|American]] [[young earth creationist]]. He is the son of "the father of [[creation science]]", [[Henry M. Morris]], and after his father's death became the president of the [[Institute for Creation Research]] (ICR). Morris is a creationist author and speaks at a variety of churches.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.icr.org/pdf/af/af0707.pdf | format=PDF | title=Intelligent Design:Strengths, Weaknesses,and the Differences | publisher=[[Institute for Creation Research]] | date=7 July 2007 | first= | last= | accessdate=2006-12-11 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713220301/http://www.icr.org/pdf/af/af0707.pdf | archivedate=13 July 2007 | df=dmy-all }} page 5</ref> Many of his presentations discuss the fossil record and its relation to evolution.<ref>{{cite video| people = John Morris |date = 2010 | title = The Fossil Record: A Problem for Evolution | url = http://vimeo.com/10259866 | medium = TV Broadcast| location = Waukesha, WI | publisher = [[VCY America]]}}</ref>

==Biography==
Morris has a B.S. in Civil Engineering from [[Virginia Tech]] (1969), an M.S., [[University of Oklahoma]] (1977), and a Ph.D., [[University of Oklahoma]] (1980) in Geological Engineering.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.answersingenesis.org/docs/326.asp | title=John D. Morris | publisher=[[Answers in Genesis]] | year=2008 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2006-12-11}} page 5</ref>  He served on the University of Oklahoma faculty.{{when|date=July 2018}} Morris held the position of Professor of Geology.{{where|date=July 2018}}

In 1984 he joined the Institute for Creation Research and in 1996 he became its president.

==Criticism==
{{undue weight|section|reason=There is no problem with having a criticism section, but having one so long in comparison with the rest of the article gives undue weight to it|date=March 2015}}
Critics have disputed some of Morris's claims. For instance, the following statement by Morris:

{{quote|From the neck down, certain clues suggested to [[Donald Johanson|Johanson]] that [[Lucy (Australopithecus)|Lucy]] walked a little more erect than today's chimps. This conclusion, based on his interpretation of the partial hip bone and a knee bone, has been hotly contested by many paleoanthropologists.<ref>Morris (1994) quoted in [http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/homs/a_piths.html Creationist Arguments: Australopithecines], [[TalkOrigins Archive]]</ref>}}

... elicited the following response from Jim Foley in [[TalkOrigins Archive]]:

{{quote|Almost everything in this quote is a distortion (Johanson's and Lucy's names are about the only exceptions). "Certain clues suggested" doesn't mention that the whole find screamed "bipedality" to every qualified scientist who looked at it. "A little more erect", when everyone believes that Lucy was fully erect. "The partial hip bone and a knee bone", when Lucy included almost a complete pelvis and leg (taking mirror imaging into account, and excluding the foot). "Has been hotly contested", when no reputable paleoanthropologist denies that Lucy was bipedal. The debates are about whether she was also arboreal, and about how similar the biomechanics of her locomotion was to that of humans. Given that we have most of Lucy's leg and pelvis, one has to wonder what sort of fossil evidence it would take to convince creationists of australopithecine bipedality.<ref>[http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/homs/a_piths.html Creationist Arguments: Australopithecines], Jim Foley, [[TalkOrigins Archive]]</ref>}}

