{{Infobox organization |name = National Socialist Women's League |nativename = ''Nationalsozialistische Frauenschaft'' |image = NS-Frauenschaft.svg |image_caption = Emblem of the NS-Frauenschaft |image_border = |size = 100px |map = |msize = |mcaption = |abbreviation = |caption = |motto = |formation = 1931 |extinction = 1945 |type = [[Women's wing]] |status = [[Denazification|Defunct]], [[Strafgesetzbuch section 86a|Illegal]] |purpose = |headquarters = |location = |region_served = [[Nazi Germany]] |language = |leader_title = |leader_name = |main_organ = |parent_organization = [[Nazi Party]] |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = |remarks = }} {{Nazism sidebar}} The '''National Socialist Women's League''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Nationalsozialistische Frauenschaft'', abbreviated ''NS-Frauenschaft'') was the [[women's wing]] of the [[Nazi Party]]. It was founded in October 1931 as a fusion of several [[nationalism|nationalist]] and [[National socialism|National Socialist]] women's associations.
The ''Frauenschaft'' was subordinated to the national party leadership (''Reichsleitung''); girls and young women were the purview of the ''[[Bund Deutscher Mädel]]'' (BDM). From February 1934 to the end of World War II in 1945, the ''NS-Frauenschaft'' was led by Reich's Women's Leader (''Reichsfrauenführerin'') [[Gertrud Scholtz-Klink]] (1902–1999). It put out a biweekly magazine, the ''[[NS-Frauen-Warte]]''.<ref>"[http://www.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/Englisch/helios/digi/nsfrauenwarte.html NS-Frauenwarte: Paper of the National Socialist Women's League]"</ref>
Its activities included instruction in the use of German-manufactured products, such as butter and rayon, in place of imported ones, as part of the self-sufficiency program, and classes for brides and schoolgirls.<ref name="Grunberger258">[[Richard Grunberger]], ''The 12-Year Reich'', p 258, {{ISBN|0-03-076435-1}}</ref> During wartime, it also provided refreshments at train stations, collected scrap metal and other materials, ran cookery and other classes, and allocated [[OST-Arbeiter#Nannies|the domestic servants conscripted in the east]] to large families.<ref name="Grunberger258"/> Propaganda organizations depended on it as the primary spreader of propaganda to women.<ref>[[Leila J. Rupp]], ''Mobilizing Women for War'', p 105, {{ISBN|0-691-04649-2}}, {{OCLC|3379930}}</ref>
The ''NS-Frauenschaft'' reached a total membership of 2 million by 1938, the equivalent of 40% of the total party membership.<ref>Payne, Stanley G. 1995 ''A History of Fascism 1914-1945'' University of Wisconsin Press, Madison p. 184</ref>
The German National Socialist Women's League Children's Group was known as ''"Kinderschar''".{{cn|date=June 2017}}
